author: @MikhailGavryuchkov
text: https://youtu.be/qcvAqAH60Yw?t=814 AUC of Logistic Regression is higher than of Random Forest (82.9% > 79.3%). At the same time, intuitively it's visible that the point on Random Forest with 18% of FPP and 80% of TPP is the best choice. What's even more interesting is that the partial AUC for 0-20% of FPP is still larger for Logistic Regression than for Random Forest. So intuitively I would choose this point of FPP=18% and TPP=80% but can't prove it mathematically.

author: @galan8115
text: For anyone that searches how to make them squared. Put "par(pty= "s")" before running the lane with the graph.   And if u got like huge margins in your graph, u need one more argument in the roc() wich is "asp=NA" ;  also you could print your AUCS easily in the plot.  My code looks like this: roc(df_mod_cand$clase, mod_cand$fitted.values, plot=T,asp=NA,col="red", lwd=3, legacy.axes=T, print.auc=TRUE)

author: @UncleLoren
text: Here's a counter-intuitive trick that helps me keep the two straight: SENSITIVITY = True POSITIVE Rate, even though the term does not have a P but does have an N.  SPECIFICITY = True NEGATIVE Rate,  even though the term does not have an N but does have a P.
